    "summary": "The Montgomery Bus Boycott was a civil rights campaign in Montgomery, Alabama, from December 1, 1955, to December 20, 1956, in which African Americans refused to ride city buses to protest segregated seating policies. The boycott began when Rosa Parks, a trained NAACP activist, was arrested for refusing to give up her seat to a white passenger. Local leaders including the newly arrived Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. organized the Montgomery Improvement Association to coordinate the boycott.\n\nFor 381 days, the Black community of Montgomery — which constituted approximately 75 percent of bus ridership — carpooled, walked, and used other means of transportation. The economic pressure on the city's bus company was severe. King's home was bombed, and organizers faced legal harassment and arrests. Nevertheless, the boycott held. The Supreme Court ultimately affirmed a lower court ruling in November 1956 that Alabama's bus segregation laws were unconstitutional.\n\nThe Montgomery Bus Boycott was a turning point in the [[event:2679|Civil Rights Movement]] for several reasons. It demonstrated that nonviolent mass economic action could succeed against segregation. It launched King as the movement's foremost national leader. And it showed that African American communities possessed the organizational discipline and solidarity to sustain a prolonged campaign. The success of Montgomery became a template for subsequent civil rights campaigns across the South.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montgomery_bus_boycott",
